WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.534 --> 00:00:06.950
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
Hey, everyone.

00:00:06.950 --> 00:00:07.850
How are you?

00:00:07.850 --> 00:00:10.350
Monday-- Monday
lunchtime, are we awake?

00:00:10.350 --> 00:00:12.380
Yeah.

00:00:12.380 --> 00:00:13.826
Hello.

00:00:13.826 --> 00:00:17.620
Idina, thank you so much
for being here and sharing

00:00:17.620 --> 00:00:19.940
with us at Google.

00:00:19.940 --> 00:00:21.190
We could not be more thrilled.

00:00:21.190 --> 00:00:24.120
And as you can see, you
got a huge lunchtime crowd

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:25.945
coming out.

00:00:25.945 --> 00:00:28.070
IDINA MENZEL: I'm only
focusing on the empty seats.

00:00:28.070 --> 00:00:28.750
Where are those people?

00:00:28.750 --> 00:00:29.791
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: Yeah.

00:00:29.791 --> 00:00:30.400
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:32.380
IDINA MENZEL: My manager hates
me because whenever I play,

00:00:32.380 --> 00:00:34.004
I'll play like a
packed house, and I'll

00:00:34.004 --> 00:00:36.570
see two people in the front
that just probably their kid got

00:00:36.570 --> 00:00:37.520
sick and they couldn't make it.

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:39.603
And I'm like, why didn't
we sell those two fucking

00:00:39.603 --> 00:00:40.434
seats in the front?

00:00:40.434 --> 00:00:41.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:41.250 --> 00:00:42.150
He's like, I did!

00:00:42.150 --> 00:00:43.620
I swear to God!

00:00:43.620 --> 00:00:44.130
I hate it.

00:00:44.130 --> 00:00:46.130
It just makes me insecure.

00:00:46.130 --> 00:00:48.089
Anyway, sorry, am I
allowed to curse at Google?

00:00:48.089 --> 00:00:49.130
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: Yeah.

00:00:49.130 --> 00:00:49.900
Yeah, you're good.

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:51.608
This is an adult
audience, so we're good.

00:00:51.608 --> 00:00:52.690
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:52.690 --> 00:00:54.690
Nobody here has ever
cursed in their whole life.

00:00:54.690 --> 00:00:57.320
I can see it now.

00:00:57.320 --> 00:00:58.420
So thank you for coming.

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:04.790
You have a new album out
and one that is, I think,

00:01:04.790 --> 00:01:07.100
somebody has told me
deeply personal to you.

00:01:07.100 --> 00:01:11.800
And would love to lead off
there of your journey and sort

00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:14.709
of what led you to this album.

00:01:14.709 --> 00:01:16.500
IDINA MENZEL: I think
most people's album's

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:18.490
deeply personal.

00:01:18.490 --> 00:01:19.930
Everybody asks me that.

00:01:19.930 --> 00:01:20.470
And it is.

00:01:20.470 --> 00:01:20.970
It's true.

00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:23.790
But I don't know.

00:01:23.790 --> 00:01:27.690
It's like whose album do we
love that isn't deeply personal?

00:01:27.690 --> 00:01:29.440
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
Right, one would hope.

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:32.165
IDINA MENZEL: But mine is.

00:01:36.990 --> 00:01:38.960
Yeah.

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:46.170
The last three
years, I guess, I had

00:01:46.170 --> 00:01:51.050
like a lot of
conflicting dynamics,

00:01:51.050 --> 00:01:52.330
I guess you could say.

00:01:52.330 --> 00:01:57.200
I was simultaneously
going through a divorce

00:01:57.200 --> 00:02:00.650
while "Frozen" was going on
its whole crazy trajectory.

00:02:00.650 --> 00:02:04.200
So I literally would go
from singing at the Oscars

00:02:04.200 --> 00:02:06.150
to heading to a
mediation agreement,

00:02:06.150 --> 00:02:09.009
discussing like
visitation about my son.

00:02:09.009 --> 00:02:15.080
So it was just
professionally speaking,

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:17.790
an incredible time, and
personally speaking,

00:02:17.790 --> 00:02:19.790
very complicated.

00:02:19.790 --> 00:02:23.640
So I had a lot to write about.

00:02:23.640 --> 00:02:28.210
And it just felt like a good
time to get back in the studio

00:02:28.210 --> 00:02:33.782
and put it into some music.

00:02:33.782 --> 00:02:35.240
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
That's awesome.

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:37.080
Thank you for going there so
early in the conversation.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:37.780
IDINA MENZEL: Personal.

00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:39.238
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
It was amazing.

00:02:41.170 --> 00:02:44.180
And as you were sort of building
the album as well and just

00:02:44.180 --> 00:02:45.870
being the theater
geek that I am,

00:02:45.870 --> 00:02:48.640
I'm thinking about the time and
place we are in theater right

00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:51.940
now, with what's happened with
"Hamilton," what we're seeing

00:02:51.940 --> 00:02:53.640
and sort of transformative.

00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:57.480
And you've really been a part of
some of the most transformative

00:02:57.480 --> 00:03:00.250
shows in theater, period.

00:03:00.250 --> 00:03:01.875
Everybody, "Rent," right?

00:03:01.875 --> 00:03:02.450
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:02.450 --> 00:03:03.616
Right, there's the applause.

00:03:03.616 --> 00:03:04.520
Yeah.

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:06.180
Right?

00:03:06.180 --> 00:03:08.763
And not to mention
"Wicked," yeah.

00:03:08.763 --> 00:03:10.260
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:10.260 --> 00:03:13.120
There we go, just
two right there.

00:03:13.120 --> 00:03:15.550
IDINA MENZEL: I do one every
10 yeare-- one zeitgeist

00:03:15.550 --> 00:03:18.380
kind of project every 10 years.

00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:22.437
And the rest I starve,
and I go into obscurity.

00:03:22.437 --> 00:03:24.020
And then all of a
sudden, I get a job,

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:25.830
and it's like, oh,
that's a big deal.

00:03:25.830 --> 00:03:28.255
And then I'm back on top again.

00:03:28.255 --> 00:03:29.630
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
You basically

00:03:29.630 --> 00:03:32.662
just drop the mic constantly.

00:03:32.662 --> 00:03:34.870
IDINA MENZEL: I wish I was
cool enough to actually do

00:03:34.870 --> 00:03:36.290
a mic drop like that.

00:03:36.290 --> 00:03:39.970
But, no, I've been
really, really lucky.

00:03:39.970 --> 00:03:42.910
But I also have experienced
the ebb and flow

00:03:42.910 --> 00:03:45.820
of this industry,
which I think is

00:03:45.820 --> 00:03:51.000
why I am able to really enjoy
it when those moments happen,

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:53.750
because I know how
fleeting they can be.

00:03:53.750 --> 00:04:03.250
So I actually, more than
ever, can get on stage

00:04:03.250 --> 00:04:09.064
and take in the moment and
realize how lucky I am.

00:04:09.064 --> 00:04:10.980
And who knows what's
going to happen tomorrow.

00:04:10.980 --> 00:04:14.580
And, wow, people showed up.

00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:18.230
But that all started with my
first professional experience,

00:04:18.230 --> 00:04:25.760
which was "Rent" and that
entire mindset of our composer

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:28.630
passing away on the
night of our first--

00:04:28.630 --> 00:04:30.820
I think it was our
invited dress, which

00:04:30.820 --> 00:04:32.490
is like the night
before an audience.

00:04:35.066 --> 00:04:36.690
Actually, no, it was
the first preview,

00:04:36.690 --> 00:04:39.550
because there was-- no,
invited dress, yeah.

00:04:39.550 --> 00:04:49.660
Anyway, so when your career
starts with that kind of event,

00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:58.130
it kind of dictates how you
see this industry and your art

00:04:58.130 --> 00:05:01.974
and gives you a perspective.

00:05:01.974 --> 00:05:03.890
And I was lucky because
we were at a young age

00:05:03.890 --> 00:05:04.681
that that happened.

00:05:04.681 --> 00:05:08.600
And we could of like lost
perspective and objectivity.

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:13.500
But instead of getting caught
up in all the magazines

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:17.410
and the accolades,
our cast actually--

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:20.300
I've never worked in any
show that this has ever

00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:22.980
happened since.

00:05:22.980 --> 00:05:28.790
Not one person missed a show
for at least six months--

00:05:28.790 --> 00:05:31.540
eight shows a week, singing
at the top of our lungss--

00:05:31.540 --> 00:05:35.360
because we were so committed,
whether we were sick or not,

00:05:35.360 --> 00:05:40.110
to getting up there and making
sure we put out his message.

00:05:40.110 --> 00:05:42.520
That was the most
important thing.

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:45.690
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
Wow, that's amazing.

00:05:45.690 --> 00:05:47.900
And with that-- I hadn't
even thought about that

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:50.351
actually in the context
of that question.

00:05:50.351 --> 00:05:52.350
Before that moment, you've
talked about the ebbs

00:05:52.350 --> 00:05:52.860
and flows.

00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:54.640
And obviously, that
was both, again,

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:57.140
at the same time that sort of
trajectory, which you talked

00:05:57.140 --> 00:06:00.690
about actually up top with
your album now as well,

00:06:00.690 --> 00:06:03.044
the conflicting
emotions of the high

00:06:03.044 --> 00:06:05.460
and the low at the same time,
which is the same thing that

00:06:05.460 --> 00:06:06.920
happened with "Rent."

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:08.420
Up to that point,
which is the stuff

00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:14.840
we can't really Google is before
"Rent," what was the seed that

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:18.530
got planted in you
wanting to do theater,

00:06:18.530 --> 00:06:21.080
wanting to sing all the time?

00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:23.580
What was that
driving force for you

00:06:23.580 --> 00:06:26.950
that led you to that sort of
first big professional moment

00:06:26.950 --> 00:06:31.470
of "Rent" that you feel
prepared you for-- or did it?

00:06:31.470 --> 00:06:33.760
IDINA MENZEL: Oh, yeah,
there are different ones.

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:36.040
It's kind of like saying
what your first love was.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:38.606
Was it the kid in
kindergarten that like

00:06:38.606 --> 00:06:39.980
kissed you on the
cheek or was it

00:06:39.980 --> 00:06:43.270
the guy you first had sex with?

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:45.220
What's first love,
really, right?

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:48.080
So that's a really bad example.

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:48.694
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:48.694 --> 00:06:49.860
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: It's OK.

00:06:49.860 --> 00:06:50.680
We're just getting real here.

00:06:50.680 --> 00:06:51.470
IDINA MENZEL: No, but I do.

00:06:51.470 --> 00:06:52.630
I always think about that.

00:06:52.630 --> 00:06:54.421
It's like when people
say first love, well,

00:06:54.421 --> 00:06:56.630
I think I really loved
this kid Evan Beller when

00:06:56.630 --> 00:06:58.590
I was in kindergarten,
but I certainly

00:06:58.590 --> 00:07:00.760
didn't let him go up
my shirt or anything.

00:07:00.760 --> 00:07:01.760
Do you know what I mean?

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:04.314
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:10.450 --> 00:07:13.100
Is it-- how early--
I think I'm tired.

00:07:13.100 --> 00:07:15.940
The album came out
this week, and I've

00:07:15.940 --> 00:07:20.110
been like surprising drag shows
and gay clubs at midnight.

00:07:20.110 --> 00:07:23.410
And I'm like, I don't know
what time zone I'm on.

00:07:23.410 --> 00:07:25.392
So you're going to get
me a little delirious

00:07:25.392 --> 00:07:29.610
and stick foot
directly into mouth.

00:07:29.610 --> 00:07:31.270
What was the question again?

00:07:31.270 --> 00:07:32.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:34.950
Oh, yeah, first,
like moment, right?

00:07:34.950 --> 00:07:36.760
Well, yes, so my
point being, it could

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:42.740
either be when my Grandfather
Nathan, Grandpa Nat would

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:45.760
put a fake toy microphone
in my hand when I was five

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:48.330
and do shows with me
in the living room.

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:55.560
Or it could be when I
sang at this talent show.

00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:59.640
We're up in the Catskills,
where the Jews all go.

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:02.930
And it was a family
trip, and our parents

00:08:02.930 --> 00:08:05.600
sent us to the day camp, and
we did this little talent show.

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:11.550
And I say "The Way We Were" with
a full-on Long Island accent.

00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:15.090
But everybody's percolating.

00:08:15.090 --> 00:08:18.430
People turned to my parents and
said, oh, she could be special.

00:08:18.430 --> 00:08:20.480
So like I don't know.

00:08:20.480 --> 00:08:22.150
There's those times.

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:26.837
And that was about
theater, yeah.

00:08:26.837 --> 00:08:29.170
Oh, it could have been the
time when my grandmother took

00:08:29.170 --> 00:08:31.760
me to see "A Star is Born"
with Barbra Streisand and Kris

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:32.990
Kristofferson.

00:08:32.990 --> 00:08:34.659
That kind of changed
my life, that idea

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:38.510
of being put on a stage
and having to win over

00:08:38.510 --> 00:08:42.760
an audience of people that were
booing you, and being so good

00:08:42.760 --> 00:08:46.110
and captivating, that it stopped
them all in their tracks.

00:08:46.110 --> 00:08:49.930
Something about that
was amazing to me.

00:08:49.930 --> 00:08:53.500
And then parents got divorced
when I was a teenager.

00:08:53.500 --> 00:08:58.050
And my mom was dating this
cool guy that really believed

00:08:58.050 --> 00:09:01.410
in me a lot and said,
you should write music,

00:09:01.410 --> 00:09:05.210
and knew some guy that was
in the wedding/bar mitzvah

00:09:05.210 --> 00:09:10.520
scene in Long Island and
helped me lie about my age,

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:14.300
because I was 15 and illegally
driving to all of these gigs,

00:09:14.300 --> 00:09:19.940
and got me a gig with Tony Syeda
and the Echoes in Oceanside.

00:09:19.940 --> 00:09:22.165
And I knew like three songs.

00:09:22.165 --> 00:09:26.120
It was "What a Feeling" from
"Flashdance," "Evergreen,"

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:32.440
and I forget that song--
like the sunshine song.

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:33.994
[HUMMING]

00:09:33.994 --> 00:09:35.160
Anyway, I can't think of it.

00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:40.470
But and then I started doing
weddings and bar mitzvahs

00:09:40.470 --> 00:09:42.280
and having to learn
all this music.

00:09:42.280 --> 00:09:43.970
And it was like an
education for me.

00:09:43.970 --> 00:09:48.680
I had to learn like Motown and
Aretha and jazz, Billie Holiday

00:09:48.680 --> 00:09:50.014
and Ella Fitzgerald.

00:09:50.014 --> 00:09:51.430
And all of a sudden
then, I didn't

00:09:51.430 --> 00:09:52.760
want to necessarily do theater.

00:09:52.760 --> 00:09:54.540
I wanted to be like a rock star.

00:09:54.540 --> 00:09:58.410
So I went back and forth between
"Annie," when I was little,

00:09:58.410 --> 00:10:03.430
and "Peter Pan" and then wanting
to write my music and record

00:10:03.430 --> 00:10:04.310
and all that.

00:10:04.310 --> 00:10:07.570
And so it's been
a constant dance

00:10:07.570 --> 00:10:10.700
for me, even till this
day, sitting here with you,

00:10:10.700 --> 00:10:14.530
trying to get people
to accept my desire

00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:19.270
to cross over from the
theater and have integrity

00:10:19.270 --> 00:10:24.230
as a rock or a pop
singer/songwriter.

00:10:24.230 --> 00:10:29.860
It's just followed
me, this little dance,

00:10:29.860 --> 00:10:34.332
trying to straddle both places
and be accepted in both.

00:10:34.332 --> 00:10:35.790
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
And do you feel

00:10:35.790 --> 00:10:38.170
like that's really--
by the way, I'm

00:10:38.170 --> 00:10:42.420
just picturing you singing
at bar mitzvahs in my head.

00:10:42.420 --> 00:10:48.060
And did you feel like with this
album, and even just looking

00:10:48.060 --> 00:10:50.720
at the track list
and people's comments

00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:54.770
really picking up on your
pop track in a real way,

00:10:54.770 --> 00:10:57.360
the intentionality there
of all the genre crossing

00:10:57.360 --> 00:11:01.500
because of your influences, what
was your thought process there?

00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:04.440
And what do you hope, as
we all listen to the album,

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:08.140
what we hear from you
as part of that journey?

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:11.820
IDINA MENZEL: Yeah,
thanks for asking that.

00:11:11.820 --> 00:11:12.700
Well, it's funny.

00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:14.340
I've done a couple
albums before this

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:17.060
that it meant more to me,
this whole crossover thing.

00:11:17.060 --> 00:11:18.180
And it didn't happen.

00:11:18.180 --> 00:11:21.240
I got dropped, or I sold like
three albums or whatever.

00:11:21.240 --> 00:11:23.510
So at this point in my
life, so many things

00:11:23.510 --> 00:11:26.390
have happened that I'm proud of.

00:11:26.390 --> 00:11:31.130
And I get up on stage
and I do a concert,

00:11:31.130 --> 00:11:38.190
and the setlist is a
chronology of my life

00:11:38.190 --> 00:11:39.470
of the songs in my life.

00:11:39.470 --> 00:11:42.730
And some of it's "Defying
Gravity" from "Wicked."

00:11:42.730 --> 00:11:44.870
And some of it's an
old Joni Mitchell song

00:11:44.870 --> 00:11:45.900
because it inspired me.

00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:48.610
And then there's "Let
It Go" from "Frozen."

00:11:48.610 --> 00:11:50.100
And then there's original music.

00:11:50.100 --> 00:11:53.270
And I used to worry that that
was confusing in some way

00:11:53.270 --> 00:11:54.550
and didn't have the cohesion.

00:11:54.550 --> 00:11:57.030
But now I realize the cohesion,
the common denominator,

00:11:57.030 --> 00:12:00.130
is me and all of my experiences.

00:12:00.130 --> 00:12:03.247
And I'm 45 years old, and
that is this is who I am.

00:12:03.247 --> 00:12:04.330
This is the life I've led.

00:12:04.330 --> 00:12:08.383
And so I kind of stopped
trying to worry-- I've

00:12:08.383 --> 00:12:10.180
got to stop worrying about it.

00:12:10.180 --> 00:12:13.130
And so when I went in
the studio this time,

00:12:13.130 --> 00:12:17.440
I picked producers that I love
that I have worked with people

00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:19.250
that I really admire.

00:12:19.250 --> 00:12:20.950
But once we got
in there, we just

00:12:20.950 --> 00:12:23.380
wrote music and hung
out and recorded,

00:12:23.380 --> 00:12:26.330
and I stopped
worrying about that.

00:12:26.330 --> 00:12:33.470
All I cared about was that
they supported me being honest

00:12:33.470 --> 00:12:36.640
and trying different things.

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:38.720
But what I think
has happened is it

00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:42.620
has a really cool, current,
mainstream kind of sound.

00:12:42.620 --> 00:12:47.100
And so hopefully-- I just want
to expand my audience, really.

00:12:47.100 --> 00:12:48.287
That's all.

00:12:48.287 --> 00:12:49.620
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: I love that.

00:12:49.620 --> 00:12:52.250
And it's really
interesting also,

00:12:52.250 --> 00:12:54.310
given the context,
interestingly,

00:12:54.310 --> 00:12:57.050
of this groundbreaking
theater you've

00:12:57.050 --> 00:13:00.630
been a part of that sort of
bent also what is theater

00:13:00.630 --> 00:13:02.700
and what the music is
that isn't theater.

00:13:02.700 --> 00:13:07.180
I'm thinking about
"Rent" rock and "Wicked"

00:13:07.180 --> 00:13:10.857
really taking us into like
full Broadway big belt number,

00:13:10.857 --> 00:13:13.190
and thinking even about the
trajectory of theater itself

00:13:13.190 --> 00:13:18.150
right now, with "Hamilton" and a
lot of experimenting happening,

00:13:18.150 --> 00:13:19.650
and also with the
advent of digital.

00:13:19.850 --> 00:13:22.360
We're here at Google and
thinking about all the artists

00:13:22.360 --> 00:13:25.230
that are sort of genre
crossing, because there's

00:13:25.230 --> 00:13:26.792
no box you have to live in.

00:13:26.792 --> 00:13:29.250
IDINA MENZEL: Exactly, and we
have more control as artists.

00:13:29.250 --> 00:13:31.340
We can put ourselves
in self promote.

00:13:31.340 --> 00:13:35.080
We don't have to rely just on
our label understanding us.

00:13:35.080 --> 00:13:39.620
We can trust the public to just
want to hear music, love music.

00:13:39.620 --> 00:13:41.730
And like so many of the
theater fans I have,

00:13:41.730 --> 00:13:45.410
there are amazing
music aficionados.

00:13:45.410 --> 00:13:46.750
They love music.

00:13:46.750 --> 00:13:48.136
They're not just theater kids.

00:13:48.136 --> 00:13:49.010
They love everything.

00:13:49.010 --> 00:13:50.801
They just love good
music and good writing.

00:13:50.801 --> 00:13:56.140
So why not just put it out there
and let the people find it?

00:13:56.140 --> 00:13:59.480
So that's really
empowering for artists now.

00:13:59.480 --> 00:14:03.090
Back in the day, when I was
trying to get a record deal

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:07.655
and playing down at the
Bitter End in the Village,

00:14:07.655 --> 00:14:10.030
it was all about just getting
a record deal and the label

00:14:10.030 --> 00:14:11.740
and being accepted
by these people.

00:14:11.740 --> 00:14:13.834
And now, as long
as you can tour,

00:14:13.834 --> 00:14:15.500
which is the most
important thing to me,

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:19.550
to be able to make a
paycheck and go out and sing

00:14:19.550 --> 00:14:23.060
and on a stage for people,
then I have the power back,

00:14:23.060 --> 00:14:24.715
which is exciting.

00:14:24.715 --> 00:14:26.090
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
It's amazing.

00:14:26.090 --> 00:14:28.700
I feel like if I took a poll
right now of the audience,

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:31.040
how many of you are just
obsessed with this woman's

00:14:31.040 --> 00:14:33.550
voice in general, right?

00:14:33.550 --> 00:14:37.310
Exactly, I think your
voice, not to say, defy,

00:14:37.310 --> 00:14:40.718
but it does, it defies
like any particular-- yeah,

00:14:40.718 --> 00:14:42.770
I know the pun was too easy.

00:14:42.770 --> 00:14:46.510
But it really does defy
any particular genre.

00:14:46.510 --> 00:14:49.097
I think we're all
obsessed with your voice

00:14:49.097 --> 00:14:50.680
and what you're
bringing as an artist.

00:14:50.680 --> 00:14:53.280
So I think in that
way, this is--

00:14:53.280 --> 00:14:56.810
IDINA MENZEL: Well, I've
been working with a voice

00:14:56.810 --> 00:14:59.180
teacher for over 20 years.

00:14:59.180 --> 00:15:03.720
She's not the kind of
teacher that you would think.

00:15:03.720 --> 00:15:07.200
Before her, when I was
younger, I studied classically.

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:10.457
But then when I started listing
to all of the other music,

00:15:10.457 --> 00:15:12.040
I thought, well, I
don't want to sound

00:15:12.040 --> 00:15:18.234
like that, like a
lot of people sound

00:15:18.234 --> 00:15:20.150
when they've been overly
trained and then they

00:15:20.150 --> 00:15:22.700
try to sing soulful
music or whatever.

00:15:27.210 --> 00:15:32.360
Her technique is
actually the untraining.

00:15:32.360 --> 00:15:34.080
She prepares me how
to breathe and keep

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:36.760
my voice so I can do eight
shows a week and not hurt myself

00:15:36.760 --> 00:15:39.120
and I can build my range
and all that stuff.

00:15:39.120 --> 00:15:41.557
So we definitely have a
regiment that I can explain,

00:15:41.557 --> 00:15:42.890
if anybody's interested in that.

00:15:42.890 --> 00:15:45.700
But the point being
it's about singing

00:15:45.700 --> 00:15:50.170
from a place of speaking as
opposed to (FANCY SINGING).

00:15:50.170 --> 00:15:52.400
That doesn't sound like
any of us talk, right?

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:54.910
So nothing against
that kind of singing.

00:15:54.910 --> 00:16:01.860
But what I gravitate to
is coming from speaking,

00:16:01.860 --> 00:16:04.920
even if it's the way I would
yell to you on the playground

00:16:04.920 --> 00:16:07.240
if I was a kid, that's just
my higher part of my voice.

00:16:07.240 --> 00:16:11.010
But it all comes from
how we would communicates

00:16:11.010 --> 00:16:14.070
as humans, our real voice.

00:16:14.070 --> 00:16:20.270
And I believe that
that's what makes

00:16:20.270 --> 00:16:22.540
gives an audience a real
connection to somebody's

00:16:22.540 --> 00:16:26.620
because they're really
talking and not performing,

00:16:26.620 --> 00:16:29.230
over-producing this sound.

00:16:29.230 --> 00:16:32.100
So I don't know why
I told you that.

00:16:32.100 --> 00:16:33.070
I forget what you said.

00:16:33.070 --> 00:16:34.260
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: No,
that's perfect because we're

00:16:34.260 --> 00:16:35.570
just having a conversation.

00:16:35.570 --> 00:16:36.952
So here we are.

00:16:36.952 --> 00:16:37.910
IDINA MENZEL: So sorry.

00:16:37.910 --> 00:16:39.050
I keep drinking the coffee.

00:16:39.050 --> 00:16:40.230
It's not really helping.

00:16:40.230 --> 00:16:42.605
Maybe it is helping, and I'm
just like, blah, blah, blah,

00:16:42.605 --> 00:16:43.149
blah.

00:16:43.149 --> 00:16:44.690
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
No, it's amazing.

00:16:44.690 --> 00:16:46.370
I think everybody's
enrapt, like sort

00:16:46.370 --> 00:16:48.660
of just shaking their head
in agreement with you--

00:16:48.660 --> 00:16:50.270
that relatability.

00:16:50.270 --> 00:16:52.730
And like you were saying
earlier, this sort of artifice

00:16:52.730 --> 00:16:56.510
between you and the audience
has disappeared in so many ways,

00:16:56.510 --> 00:16:59.030
that that connection of what
you're talking about, really

00:16:59.030 --> 00:17:02.970
singing in a way that's
accessible to human speaking--

00:17:02.970 --> 00:17:05.290
IDINA MENZEL: Yeah, the only
thing working against that

00:17:05.290 --> 00:17:10.050
is that we all listen
to music that's

00:17:10.050 --> 00:17:14.210
been fixed and auto-tuned
so much, that now

00:17:14.210 --> 00:17:20.079
what is perfect and
imperfect can be debated.

00:17:20.079 --> 00:17:23.000
And when you go
to a live concert,

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.359
are you really
hearing people or not?

00:17:25.359 --> 00:17:27.089
And so when you
actually hear someone

00:17:27.089 --> 00:17:32.220
that chooses to actually sing,
even when she has a bad cold

00:17:32.220 --> 00:17:34.780
or it's that time of month
or she was up at 3:00

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:37.450
in the morning with her son
or fighting with her boyfriend

00:17:37.450 --> 00:17:46.030
and I don't sound
perfect, it's taken some

00:17:46.030 --> 00:17:48.140
of the love out of it for me.

00:17:48.140 --> 00:17:50.900
The social media
takes a lot out of it

00:17:50.900 --> 00:17:55.190
because I read it,
like an asshole.

00:17:55.190 --> 00:17:59.430
And you know that people
can just go on there

00:17:59.430 --> 00:18:01.290
and immediately talk
about everything.

00:18:01.290 --> 00:18:07.380
And so it's made it
harder to enjoy it.

00:18:07.380 --> 00:18:10.960
I have to really kind of
like turn it off and find

00:18:10.960 --> 00:18:12.990
the love of singing,
and also remember

00:18:12.990 --> 00:18:18.400
that there have been many shows
where I've sung and not been

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:21.331
at the top of my game, and
people still are in tears

00:18:21.331 --> 00:18:22.330
or still feel something.

00:18:22.330 --> 00:18:23.870
And I remember, oh,
it's not because I

00:18:23.870 --> 00:18:26.244
hit a really high note that
makes someone feel something.

00:18:26.244 --> 00:18:29.160
It's because what you're
communicating as a person.

00:18:29.160 --> 00:18:30.460
So I have to remember that.

00:18:30.460 --> 00:18:33.427
But my whole life has been
about-- my entire identity

00:18:33.427 --> 00:18:35.760
has been based on the fact
that when I was a young girl,

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:37.170
I had this voice.

00:18:37.170 --> 00:18:38.590
And so as I've
gotten older, I've

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:42.290
had to understand that I have
a lot more to offer the world

00:18:42.290 --> 00:18:45.390
than just being a singer.

00:18:45.390 --> 00:18:47.785
But sometimes I forget myself.

00:18:47.785 --> 00:18:49.160
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
Well, it also

00:18:49.160 --> 00:18:50.534
comes from even
the earlier days.

00:18:50.534 --> 00:18:52.790
You were saying you
were sort of taught

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:55.800
to think about
songwriting very early on,

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:59.190
which I would imagine has
actually helped in terms

00:18:59.190 --> 00:19:03.150
of thinking beyond just where
the pigeon holes might be

00:19:03.150 --> 00:19:05.480
with people thinking about you.

00:19:05.480 --> 00:19:09.590
And with that, were
there any, for you,

00:19:09.590 --> 00:19:14.720
defining moments in your career,
either joyous or really tough?

00:19:14.720 --> 00:19:16.220
I know we talked a
bit about "Rent."

00:19:16.220 --> 00:19:18.900
But has there been any
other moments for use

00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:22.420
that just really stand out as
an artist, or maybe in a moment

00:19:22.420 --> 00:19:25.000
there you suddenly
felt like you had

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:28.630
defied maybe one of those boxes
that somebody had maybe put you

00:19:28.630 --> 00:19:31.290
in?

00:19:31.290 --> 00:19:33.890
IDINA MENZEL: Yeah, well,
the success of "Let It

00:19:33.890 --> 00:19:39.360
Go" and "Frozen" because you
said like with "Rent," that it

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:42.784
was this rock-pop musical.

00:19:42.784 --> 00:19:45.200
And you would think that then
that would open doors for me

00:19:45.200 --> 00:19:49.370
to be able to walk between
all of these lines.

00:19:49.370 --> 00:19:49.960
But it wasn't.

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:54.380
Whenever I'd go into a recording
studio with a big-time producer

00:19:54.380 --> 00:19:56.730
or a songwriter, they'd
sort of admonish me

00:19:56.730 --> 00:20:00.960
and say like, oh,
you're too expressive.

00:20:00.960 --> 00:20:02.850
It's all that Broadway training.

00:20:02.850 --> 00:20:05.070
Or you have to sound
more like Sheryl Crow.

00:20:05.070 --> 00:20:05.950
Throw it away.

00:20:10.790 --> 00:20:11.455
So, I'm sorry.

00:20:11.455 --> 00:20:12.580
I lost my train of thought.

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:15.229
So then-- help me.

00:20:15.229 --> 00:20:16.770
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
Defining moments,

00:20:16.770 --> 00:20:17.890
where you sort of broke the box.

00:20:17.890 --> 00:20:18.380
IDINA MENZEL: Oh, yeah.

00:20:18.380 --> 00:20:20.130
And so they would have
all of these rules,

00:20:20.130 --> 00:20:22.250
like theater people
are never going

00:20:22.250 --> 00:20:23.870
to get on the radio
on a pop station.

00:20:23.870 --> 00:20:28.940
And then all of a sudden, cut
to like 15 years later, I'm

00:20:28.940 --> 00:20:30.800
taking my kid to
school and Z100's on,

00:20:30.800 --> 00:20:32.330
and I hear "Let It Go."

00:20:32.330 --> 00:20:35.160
I'm like, what the hell?

00:20:35.160 --> 00:20:37.530
You can't worry
about those rules.

00:20:37.530 --> 00:20:39.150
And I did for a long time.

00:20:39.150 --> 00:20:41.630
You've just got to keep
moving and going and taking

00:20:41.630 --> 00:20:43.450
work that makes you feel good.

00:20:43.450 --> 00:20:47.050
And surround yourself with
people that teach you stuff,

00:20:47.050 --> 00:20:48.470
and just keep going.

00:20:48.470 --> 00:20:49.900
Because the trends
and the rules,

00:20:49.900 --> 00:20:52.250
they always break
and move and change.

00:20:52.250 --> 00:20:54.790
And all of a sudden,
you hear like a bridge.

00:20:54.790 --> 00:20:56.590
Like, what's a bridge
in "Let It Go?"

00:20:56.590 --> 00:20:59.570
It's like a, "frozen
fractals all around."

00:20:59.570 --> 00:21:01.070
There's like these
crazy lyrics that

00:21:01.070 --> 00:21:02.654
would never be in a pop song.

00:21:02.654 --> 00:21:04.320
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
The word "fractals?"

00:21:04.320 --> 00:21:05.115
IDINA MENZEL: Yeah.

00:21:05.115 --> 00:21:06.851
Who rhymes with fractals?

00:21:06.851 --> 00:21:07.350
Not me.

00:21:07.350 --> 00:21:08.300
I didn't write it.

00:21:08.300 --> 00:21:11.080
But you know?

00:21:11.080 --> 00:21:14.980
But it's become like this
huge pop culture moment.

00:21:14.980 --> 00:21:19.020
So go figure and fuck all those
people that like wrote me off.

00:21:19.020 --> 00:21:23.930
So that was a big defining
moment, a teaching moment

00:21:23.930 --> 00:21:27.417
for me, just to know you just
can't keep following a trend.

00:21:27.417 --> 00:21:29.750
Because by the time you get
there, it's changed already.

00:21:29.750 --> 00:21:31.200
So just keep doing your thing.

00:21:34.510 --> 00:21:37.940
This album's a big
deal just because I

00:21:37.940 --> 00:21:43.050
was with my ex-husband for--
we were married a long time,

00:21:43.050 --> 00:21:45.510
but together even
longer, so like 16 years

00:21:45.510 --> 00:21:49.630
and grew up together.

00:21:49.630 --> 00:21:52.060
So to figure out how
to separate yourself,

00:21:52.060 --> 00:21:54.610
who you are separate
from that person

00:21:54.610 --> 00:22:01.110
and to be creative without
worrying about what he would

00:22:01.110 --> 00:22:07.440
think was interesting and
liberating, too, to just get

00:22:07.440 --> 00:22:12.430
in the studio and
go and not worry--

00:22:12.430 --> 00:22:16.730
and figuring out how to stop
regretting all of that stuff

00:22:16.730 --> 00:22:22.340
and pave the way for some
new exciting stuff to happen.

00:22:22.340 --> 00:22:25.555
I got engaged recently.

00:22:25.555 --> 00:22:28.740
[APPLAUSE]

00:22:28.740 --> 00:22:30.240
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
Congratulations.

00:22:30.240 --> 00:22:32.259
IDINA MENZEL: Thanks.

00:22:32.259 --> 00:22:34.300
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: With
that, just thinking even

00:22:34.300 --> 00:22:37.020
about "Let It Go"
and the new album

00:22:37.020 --> 00:22:39.960
and where they came
from, the journey,

00:22:39.960 --> 00:22:42.370
I think, at least
from what I've seen,

00:22:42.370 --> 00:22:45.360
and I work a lot on inclusion
issues and representation

00:22:45.360 --> 00:22:47.302
issues as part of my day job.

00:22:47.302 --> 00:22:49.260
IDINA MENZEL: I was just
in the bathroom stall,

00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:51.070
and there's a thing
about inclusion

00:22:51.070 --> 00:22:52.950
as I was sitting on the toilet.

00:22:52.950 --> 00:22:55.224
You put a thing in front
of me about inclusion.

00:22:55.224 --> 00:22:56.890
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
Learning on the Loo.

00:22:56.890 --> 00:22:58.870
IDINA MENZEL: Learning
on Loo, OK, got it.

00:22:58.870 --> 00:23:00.269
Well, I was reading it.

00:23:00.269 --> 00:23:01.810
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
It was effective.

00:23:01.810 --> 00:23:04.974
If somebody's in here
who did that-- fantastic.

00:23:04.974 --> 00:23:07.170
[INAUDIBLE] at Google.

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:11.070
And the fun part
about that is we

00:23:11.070 --> 00:23:13.600
work with a lot of
artists who are viewed

00:23:13.600 --> 00:23:15.900
as role models in the industry.

00:23:15.900 --> 00:23:18.420
And as our friend Gina Davis
says, if you can see it,

00:23:18.420 --> 00:23:19.890
you can be it.

00:23:19.890 --> 00:23:22.570
And given "Frozen," you brought
up "Frozen" and "Let It Go,"

00:23:22.570 --> 00:23:24.640
and now actually, sort
of defining yourself

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:30.180
entirely in this way with the
album in this new moment, who

00:23:30.180 --> 00:23:32.990
was a role model in your life?

00:23:32.990 --> 00:23:36.660
And have you felt that
that idea of a role model

00:23:36.660 --> 00:23:41.380
fall on you now, given how
many little girls and boys kind

00:23:41.380 --> 00:23:45.030
of latched on to your music, who
may have not known you before?

00:23:45.030 --> 00:23:47.690
What's that been like,
and can you trace it

00:23:47.690 --> 00:23:49.870
to somebody in your own life?

00:23:49.870 --> 00:23:52.409
IDINA MENZEL: Yeah, well,
first of all, my sister's

00:23:52.409 --> 00:23:53.450
a huge role model for me.

00:23:53.450 --> 00:23:55.930
She's my younger sister-- 3
and 1/2 years younger than me.

00:23:55.930 --> 00:24:00.630
But she got married
and had kids before me,

00:24:00.630 --> 00:24:02.780
so our roles reversed
in a lot of ways.

00:24:02.780 --> 00:24:05.670
I'd go to her for the
wisdom of certain things.

00:24:05.670 --> 00:24:14.330
And she got remarried, so she
went through a bunch of crap

00:24:14.330 --> 00:24:18.420
and handled it so gracefully.

00:24:18.420 --> 00:24:22.020
She was single and had these two
little tiny boys at the time.

00:24:22.020 --> 00:24:26.070
And because she grew up with a
sister, that was always like,

00:24:26.070 --> 00:24:27.550
I know what I'm
doing with my life.

00:24:27.550 --> 00:24:29.290
I'm singing, I
want to be famous.

00:24:29.290 --> 00:24:31.420
And she was like, I
have no idea what to do,

00:24:31.420 --> 00:24:34.180
and I have this
annoying sister's shadow

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:35.800
to walk around in.

00:24:35.800 --> 00:24:37.440
It took her longer
to figure out what

00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:38.731
she wanted to do with her life.

00:24:38.731 --> 00:24:40.710
And then she did.

00:24:40.710 --> 00:24:43.150
She's this amazing
teacher and a writer.

00:24:43.150 --> 00:24:46.010
She's writing a
book, but she did it.

00:24:46.010 --> 00:24:47.899
She went back to school
and got her masters

00:24:47.899 --> 00:24:48.940
with the two little kids.

00:24:48.940 --> 00:24:54.320
And so anyway, just
her strength and grace,

00:24:54.320 --> 00:24:57.865
really, has been an
inspiration to me.

00:24:57.865 --> 00:25:02.300
She's super, super
smart and eloquent.

00:25:02.300 --> 00:25:04.640
The role model thing with
me and the characters

00:25:04.640 --> 00:25:07.460
I played, and they're always
connecting to young audiences

00:25:07.460 --> 00:25:13.070
is a beautiful thing, and it's
also a daunting responsibility.

00:25:13.070 --> 00:25:15.420
One, is that the
age disparity is

00:25:15.420 --> 00:25:16.790
getting even bigger and bigger.

00:25:16.790 --> 00:25:23.900
So now, like the "Frozen" thing,
there's like six-year-olds,

00:25:23.900 --> 00:25:25.310
and then there's me coming.

00:25:25.310 --> 00:25:26.830
So like I do a concert.

00:25:26.830 --> 00:25:29.347
I'm on stage, talking
like a truck driver.

00:25:29.347 --> 00:25:30.930
And then I look down,
and there's just

