lucky enough as a kid.

00:28:17.370 --> 00:28:20.280
My parents would send me
away to sleepaway camp.

00:28:20.280 --> 00:28:22.750
It's a Jewish East
Coast thing to do.

00:28:22.750 --> 00:28:26.670
And it was a privileged thing.

00:28:26.670 --> 00:28:29.270
But it was a wonderful
experience, an opportunity

00:28:29.270 --> 00:28:32.880
to escape, to kind of
rewrite yourself as a kid

00:28:32.880 --> 00:28:35.240
if you didn't enjoy
your school year.

00:28:35.240 --> 00:28:37.140
It's a place to bond
and make new friends

00:28:37.140 --> 00:28:41.180
and find yourself, really.

00:28:41.180 --> 00:28:42.960
And I always wanted
to have a camp.

00:28:42.960 --> 00:28:49.150
And then as I got
older and I started

00:28:49.150 --> 00:28:53.200
to have these experiences
and these projects where

00:28:53.200 --> 00:28:59.180
it was connecting to
young women, especially,

00:28:59.180 --> 00:29:00.980
young women trying
to find their voice,

00:29:00.980 --> 00:29:03.500
I realized that the camp
had to be more than just

00:29:03.500 --> 00:29:05.080
what I experienced
when I was younger

00:29:05.080 --> 00:29:08.310
and be more
meaningful than that.

00:29:08.310 --> 00:29:12.490
And so my college roommate,
who's much smarter than me,

00:29:12.490 --> 00:29:14.670
and was sick and
tired of hearing me

00:29:14.670 --> 00:29:16.660
talk about this pipe dream.

00:29:16.660 --> 00:29:18.480
And so she galvanized
the whole thing.

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:21.730
She's a business major,
lawyer, type-A person,

00:29:21.730 --> 00:29:23.180
got the thing together.

00:29:23.180 --> 00:29:26.090
And it's called The Broader Way.

00:29:26.090 --> 00:29:29.210
And we're going on
our seventh year.

00:29:29.210 --> 00:29:32.020
It's a 10-day
program, where we take

00:29:32.020 --> 00:29:33.610
a bunch of inner-city
girls, mostly

00:29:33.610 --> 00:29:36.700
from Harlem and the
Lower East Side,

00:29:36.700 --> 00:29:41.650
up to the Berkshire Mountains
in Massachusetts for 10 days

00:29:41.650 --> 00:29:45.210
to like a college campus that
we lease the property for now.

00:29:45.210 --> 00:29:49.260
Eventually, hopefully,
we'll have our own place.

00:29:49.260 --> 00:29:51.100
And we sing, and we
dance, and we swam.

00:29:51.100 --> 00:29:57.020
And Jeanine Tesori, who's an
incredible Broadway composer,

00:29:57.020 --> 00:29:59.810
wrote "Fun Home"
and a ton of things.

00:29:59.810 --> 00:30:02.160
She's kind of like
my creative director.

00:30:02.160 --> 00:30:05.680
And we bring up amazing
veteran performers

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:07.140
that come and work with them.

00:30:07.140 --> 00:30:09.780
But the whole thing is not
to put on like "Oklahoma"

00:30:09.780 --> 00:30:12.040
with these girls.

00:30:12.040 --> 00:30:15.900
We encourage them
to write a lot.

00:30:15.900 --> 00:30:17.550
They do a lot of spoken word.

00:30:17.550 --> 00:30:19.270
They write their
own songs, lyrics.

00:30:19.270 --> 00:30:22.660
They choreograph
their own movement.

00:30:22.660 --> 00:30:24.530
And so at the end
of the 10 days,

00:30:24.530 --> 00:30:29.400
they come back into New York
to a theater that's usually,

00:30:29.400 --> 00:30:31.380
thankfully, given
to us for the night.

00:30:31.380 --> 00:30:35.270
And we put on a recital,
concert, if you will,

00:30:35.270 --> 00:30:48.550
that's a complete collage
of their original work.

00:30:48.550 --> 00:30:52.720
So it's-- and so we started
with 30 girls the first year.

00:30:52.720 --> 00:30:54.490
And now it's become
a four-year program.

00:30:54.490 --> 00:30:57.980
