00:36:51.228 --> 00:36:51.936
IDINA MENZEL: No.

00:36:54.282 --> 00:36:55.490
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: Progress?

00:36:59.860 --> 00:37:02.310
IDINA MENZEL: Oh, I'm
going to be honest?

00:37:02.310 --> 00:37:03.810
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
Yeah, be honest.

00:37:03.810 --> 00:37:05.890
IDINA MENZEL: The name
of my boyfriend/fiance--

00:37:05.890 --> 00:37:06.680
I hate that word.

00:37:06.680 --> 00:37:08.310
His name's Aaron.

00:37:08.310 --> 00:37:10.280
Progress-- I don't
know why he popped in.

00:37:10.280 --> 00:37:16.640
I think because he's-- yeah,
because I think he makes me

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:18.060
a better person.

00:37:18.060 --> 00:37:19.700
He used to be an actor.

00:37:19.700 --> 00:37:24.290
But now he's this amazing
addiction specialist

00:37:24.290 --> 00:37:26.090
and has his master's
in psychology

00:37:26.090 --> 00:37:29.430
and works in this rehab.

00:37:29.430 --> 00:37:35.190
And he's a Neanderthal,
but he communicates well.

00:37:35.190 --> 00:37:41.770
And he's just-- I feel like I'm
my best self when I'm with him.

00:37:41.770 --> 00:37:45.200
So I hate that I made it
about a man, but I did.

00:37:45.200 --> 00:37:47.450
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: Here we
are, progress [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:47.450 --> 00:37:49.870
We'll try another one-- music.

00:37:54.560 --> 00:37:57.220
IDINA MENZEL: Walker came
into my mind, my son, Walker,

00:37:57.220 --> 00:38:00.745
because I finally-- he
hates Mommy singing.

00:38:00.745 --> 00:38:01.495
He hates "Frozen."

00:38:01.495 --> 00:38:03.870
He hates it all.

00:38:03.870 --> 00:38:07.200
But I got him to sit down
at the piano with me.

00:38:07.200 --> 00:38:11.050
I just shipped my piano from
New York to my new house in LA.

00:38:11.050 --> 00:38:13.630
And I got him to sit with me.

00:38:15.900 --> 00:38:17.600
You can't tell my
son to do something.

00:38:17.600 --> 00:38:18.870
He has find it on his own.

00:38:18.870 --> 00:38:21.910
Otherwise, he's
like-- but we started

00:38:21.910 --> 00:38:24.250
writing a little song
on the piano together.

00:38:24.250 --> 00:38:31.750
And we titled it, and it was
called-- what was it called?

00:38:31.750 --> 00:38:33.669
"The Fire House" or something.

00:38:33.669 --> 00:38:34.210
I don't know.

00:38:34.210 --> 00:38:36.560
Anyway, it was a lot
of scary bass notes

00:38:36.560 --> 00:38:39.800
because he's into
zombies and werewolves.

00:38:39.800 --> 00:38:41.390
But that was music
to me, because I've

00:38:41.390 --> 00:38:43.870
been waiting to have a
moment where I could somehow

00:38:43.870 --> 00:38:47.190
inspire him with my musicality.

00:38:47.190 --> 00:38:49.661
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: I love that.

00:38:49.661 --> 00:38:50.160
Theater?

00:38:58.550 --> 00:39:00.210
IDINA MENZEL: Home.

00:39:00.210 --> 00:39:02.070
Theater is home to me.

00:39:02.070 --> 00:39:05.700
No matter what has happened
in my career, ups and downs,

00:39:05.700 --> 00:39:06.940
I always can go back.

00:39:06.940 --> 00:39:09.520
And I end up falling
into a wonderful show.

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:11.930
Whether it's hugely
successful or not,

00:39:11.930 --> 00:39:15.982
I have this experience
with a cast and community.

00:39:19.260 --> 00:39:22.410
Recording music is sort of more
of more solitary experience.

00:39:22.410 --> 00:39:32.440
And theater is family,
so, yeah, home.

00:39:32.440 --> 00:39:33.870
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: And time?

00:39:33.870 --> 00:39:35.078
IDINA MENZEL: Time-- T-I-M-E?

00:39:35.078 --> 00:39:37.594
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: Yeah, time.

00:39:37.594 --> 00:39:44.530
IDINA MENZEL: (SIGHING)
Time-- I'm blanking.

00:39:44.530 --> 00:39:52.220
Time-- time for me is age maybe.

00:39:52.220 --> 00:39:56.140
Yeah, the man wants
me to have a baby,

00:39:56.140 --> 00:39:59.880
and I'm like, just
forget it, man.

00:39:59.880 --> 00:40:00.750
So it's time.

00:40:00.750 --> 00:40:03.220
Like is there enough time?

00:40:03.220 --> 00:40:07.260
And if there is, do I even
want to do that with this time?

00:40:07.260 --> 00:40:12.630
Or do I want to travel
and have a life now?

00:40:12.630 --> 00:40:15.771
So it's kind of about
the clock ticking time.

00:40:15.771 --> 00:40:17.020
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: I love it.

00:40:17.020 --> 00:40:18.601
One last one-- joy.

00:40:18.601 --> 00:40:19.350
IDINA MENZEL: Joy?

00:40:19.350 --> 00:40:20.400
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: Yeah.

00:40:20.400 --> 00:40:21.941
IDINA MENZEL: Yeah,
joy is jumping on

00:40:21.941 --> 00:40:26.130
the-- it's the trampoline that
I built at my house-- jumping

00:40:26.130 --> 00:40:29.270
both boys, total
release of energy,

00:40:29.270 --> 00:40:32.730
just jumping on a trampoline.

00:40:32.730 --> 00:40:35.960
It's like so much fun.

00:40:35.960 --> 00:40:37.210
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: I love it.

00:40:37.210 --> 00:40:39.120
And with that, I'd love to
turn it over to the audience.

00:40:39.120 --> 00:40:40.830
We have some mics in the middle.

00:40:40.830 --> 00:40:42.874
Anybody want to come
up and ask a question?

00:40:42.874 --> 00:40:46.450
Oh, we already have one.

00:40:46.450 --> 00:40:47.240
Excellent.

00:40:47.240 --> 00:40:49.031
IDINA MENZEL: It's
funny you have the mics.

00:40:49.031 --> 00:40:50.570
You probably can just ask me.

00:40:50.570 --> 00:40:52.519
I probably don't even need this.

00:40:52.519 --> 00:40:53.310
AUDIENCE: Hi there.

00:40:53.310 --> 00:40:55.410
My name is Shannon.

00:40:55.410 --> 00:40:58.310
First of all, I just want
to make a comment before.

00:40:58.310 --> 00:40:59.430
Thank you for coming out.

00:40:59.430 --> 00:41:02.350
And I just want to
tell you that I grew up

00:41:02.350 --> 00:41:04.120
like just so looking up to you.

00:41:04.120 --> 00:41:05.080
I lived in Arizona.

00:41:05.080 --> 00:41:07.560
And I'm sure we
all listened to you

00:41:07.560 --> 00:41:09.550
and maybe didn't get
to see you on Broadway.

00:41:09.550 --> 00:41:11.910
And it was so cool because
you came here to the Greek.

00:41:11.910 --> 00:41:13.743
It was your first time,
I think, performing.

00:41:13.743 --> 00:41:15.070
And I came and saw you.

00:41:15.070 --> 00:41:17.910
And it was awesome
because you were so real.

00:41:17.910 --> 00:41:20.580
I loved even just the
times in between the music

00:41:20.580 --> 00:41:22.480
more than like your
actual singing.

00:41:22.480 --> 00:41:26.180
So it's cool to see
you, to be honest.

00:41:26.180 --> 00:41:27.590
IDINA MENZEL: I appreciate that.

00:41:27.590 --> 00:41:29.820
AUDIENCE: So I just say,
like I'm sure, in case

00:41:29.820 --> 00:41:30.870
you don't hear it
enough, because you

00:41:30.870 --> 00:41:32.480
said about the social
and I'm sure there

00:41:32.480 --> 00:41:33.771
are people saying good and bad.

00:41:33.771 --> 00:41:37.010
But like keep being like
you and authentic and real

00:41:37.010 --> 00:41:39.310
because like people
do respect that.

00:41:39.310 --> 00:41:41.137
IDINA MENZEL: Thank you.

00:41:41.137 --> 00:41:42.720
AUDIENCE: Now I'll
get to my question.

00:41:42.720 --> 00:41:47.180
So I'm always fascinated by like
how people prepare for roles.

00:41:47.180 --> 00:41:51.310
And so I'd love to hear about
when you prepared how was it

00:41:51.310 --> 00:41:54.450
like preparing for like Maureen
an Elphaba and that time

00:41:54.450 --> 00:41:56.710
in your life versus
preparing for like Liz, which

00:41:56.710 --> 00:41:58.930
was like you're kind of
come back to New York,

00:41:58.930 --> 00:42:01.840
and maybe that character
reflected more of like you?

00:42:01.840 --> 00:42:02.650
Or I don't know.

00:42:02.650 --> 00:42:04.700
I'm just maybe guessing.

00:42:04.700 --> 00:42:06.880
And then how you prepare
for like your album,

00:42:06.880 --> 00:42:11.610
like how does it like juxtapose
the preparation for a character

00:42:11.610 --> 00:42:12.947
versus like--

00:42:12.947 --> 00:42:15.030
IDINA MENZEL: Well, there's
technical preparation,

00:42:15.030 --> 00:42:18.190
which if it involves
music, then there's

00:42:18.190 --> 00:42:20.510
like the singing
aspect, literally

00:42:20.510 --> 00:42:25.020
the athleticism of
what that entails

00:42:25.020 --> 00:42:28.880
and preparing that, which means
the teacher I told you about.

00:42:28.880 --> 00:42:32.284
It means like treating
myself, like if you were going

00:42:32.284 --> 00:42:33.950
to run the marathon,
you wouldn't go run

00:42:33.950 --> 00:42:35.540
26 miles out of nowhere, right?

00:42:35.540 --> 00:42:36.280
You'd build up.

00:42:36.280 --> 00:42:38.590
So I do all of this preparation.

00:42:38.590 --> 00:42:39.554
I meet with her.

00:42:39.554 --> 00:42:40.720
We go through all the music.

00:42:40.720 --> 00:42:41.850
We pick all the things.

00:42:41.850 --> 00:42:44.200
Like, oh, that's going
to be hard on a matinee.

00:42:44.200 --> 00:42:48.999
And like I start singing
a certain amount of time.

00:42:48.999 --> 00:42:51.540
I literally little time myself--
15 minutes a day for a week.

00:42:51.540 --> 00:42:52.760
And then I start to move it up.

00:42:52.760 --> 00:42:54.509
And all of a sudden,
my voice gets bigger,

00:42:54.509 --> 00:42:55.940
and the range gets bigger.

00:42:55.940 --> 00:42:59.780
And so I treat that
like an athlete.

00:42:59.780 --> 00:43:01.830
And then as far
as characters go,

00:43:01.830 --> 00:43:04.930
it's changed because
I feel like I

00:43:04.930 --> 00:43:08.481
have more of a technique and a
process as I've gotten older.

00:43:08.481 --> 00:43:10.230
When I was younger, I
used to kind of just

00:43:10.230 --> 00:43:11.280
throw it out there.

00:43:15.030 --> 00:43:20.650
But how do I prepare?

00:43:25.420 --> 00:43:28.430
It's more to me
about the words, less

00:43:28.430 --> 00:43:31.140
about worrying about how does
it feel to wear green makeup.

00:43:33.770 --> 00:43:36.090
I mean, I went and
watched "The Wizard of Oz"

00:43:36.090 --> 00:43:40.490
and like watched
Margaret Hamilton.

00:43:40.490 --> 00:43:45.440
But that was just to kind of get
some cool ideas to play off of

00:43:45.440 --> 00:43:48.840
and a fun cackle and
her laugh, whatever.

00:43:48.840 --> 00:43:55.050
But for the most part, it's
about the language, the words,

00:43:55.050 --> 00:44:01.310
knowing them in such a way that
it's like song in a way, to me.

00:44:01.310 --> 00:44:06.310
It's like jazz, so I can just
be in the moment and riff off

00:44:06.310 --> 00:44:06.820
of that.

00:44:11.010 --> 00:44:14.030
Yeah, it's about knowing that
so well, that you can just

00:44:14.030 --> 00:44:16.150
be open and receive.

00:44:16.150 --> 00:44:23.060
So I'm not giving a good
explanation of that.

00:44:23.060 --> 00:44:24.435
AUDIENCE: No that
was good, yeah.

00:44:24.435 --> 00:44:25.840
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: I
think that was great.

00:44:25.840 --> 00:44:26.673
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:26.673 --> 00:44:28.358
IDINA MENZEL: Thank you.

00:44:28.358 --> 00:44:29.358
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: Yes?

00:44:33.360 --> 00:44:37.750
AUDIENCE: So when you are in
the middle of a run on Broadway

00:44:37.750 --> 00:44:40.730
or something, what is
your daily routine like?

00:44:40.730 --> 00:44:41.850
What's it really like?

00:44:41.850 --> 00:44:44.090
Are you one of those
people that rolls out

00:44:44.090 --> 00:44:45.917
of bed at noon and then--

00:44:45.917 --> 00:44:46.750
IDINA MENZEL: I was.

00:44:46.750 --> 00:44:48.645
AUDIENCE: Because
you work late, right?

00:44:48.645 --> 00:44:50.160
IDINA MENZEL: Yeah, that's
what's so hard about it.

00:44:50.160 --> 00:44:50.750
AUDIENCE: What is
that day really like?

00:44:50.750 --> 00:44:51.950
I'd like to get a picture?

00:44:51.950 --> 00:44:54.066
IDINA MENZEL: OK,
well, there's pre-baby,

00:44:54.066 --> 00:44:55.190
and then there's post-baby.

00:44:55.190 --> 00:44:57.270
AUDIENCE: Well, also,
secondarily, I'm

00:44:57.270 --> 00:44:58.870
sure it was
different now than it

00:44:58.870 --> 00:44:59.920
was when you were doing "Rent."

00:44:59.920 --> 00:45:00.711
IDINA MENZEL: Yeah.

00:45:00.711 --> 00:45:06.040
No, it's sleep, sleep, sleep is
the best feeling for a voice,

00:45:06.040 --> 00:45:10.090
first of all-- so as much
they pursue possible always.

00:45:10.090 --> 00:45:12.370
But sometimes you can't.

00:45:12.370 --> 00:45:14.814
And if you're nervous, you
don't sleep well either

00:45:14.814 --> 00:45:15.730
like the night before.

00:45:15.730 --> 00:45:19.190
But when you're in like
a routine, I come home.

00:45:19.190 --> 00:45:20.160
I watch a movie.

00:45:20.160 --> 00:45:22.880
I'm wound up.

00:45:22.880 --> 00:45:25.200
So I get home, and I'm
up late because I still

00:45:25.200 --> 00:45:25.980
can't go to sleep.

00:45:25.980 --> 00:45:27.070
I just did a performance.

00:45:27.070 --> 00:45:29.960
So that adrenaline
is still wearing off.

00:45:29.960 --> 00:45:34.170
So then, yeah, sleep in,
I steam all the time.

00:45:34.170 --> 00:45:35.190
I'm like a big steamer.

00:45:35.190 --> 00:45:37.199
So I will sit like in a shower.

00:45:37.199 --> 00:45:38.365
I'm not good for California.

00:45:38.365 --> 00:45:39.700
I waste a lot of water.

00:45:39.700 --> 00:45:41.510
But I like steam.

00:45:41.510 --> 00:45:51.110
I vocalize and then make
my way over to the theater.

00:45:51.110 --> 00:45:54.000
But with the child,
it's just changed it.

00:45:54.000 --> 00:46:00.870
Because all of a sudden,
I couldn't get the sleep.

00:46:00.870 --> 00:46:04.315
Everything was just
thrown up in upheaval.

00:46:07.020 --> 00:46:10.042
I feel like I end up enjoying
myself more on stage now

00:46:10.042 --> 00:46:13.610
that I have a child because I'm
like, well, I can't be perfect.

00:46:13.610 --> 00:46:15.870
So what can I do?

00:46:15.870 --> 00:46:17.870
He had a fever, and I'm
trying to be a good mom.

00:46:17.870 --> 00:46:18.770
So I get up there.

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:20.740
And then I end up doing
better because I'm

00:46:20.740 --> 00:46:23.160
more relaxed, because I just
throw caution to the wind.

00:46:23.160 --> 00:46:26.710
As opposed to like I
warmed up for 25 minutes,

00:46:26.710 --> 00:46:29.389
and I didn't drink any wine, and
I didn't smoke any cigarettes,

00:46:29.389 --> 00:46:31.180
and I'm perfect, perfect,
perfect, and then

00:46:31.180 --> 00:46:33.210
I still miss the
note-- oh, my, god.

00:46:33.210 --> 00:46:39.392
So now I'm more of a human
being, and I enjoy myself more.

00:46:39.392 --> 00:46:40.350
AUDIENCE: That's great.

00:46:40.350 --> 00:46:40.850
Thank you.

00:46:44.160 --> 00:46:46.000
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
Another one, yes.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:48.949
AUDIENCE: First off,
congratulations on your album.

00:46:48.949 --> 00:46:50.990
As another parent, I really
enjoyed the sentiment

00:46:50.990 --> 00:46:53.750
in "Perfect Story."

00:46:53.750 --> 00:46:57.650
Now more of a story of
myself, because after I

00:46:57.650 --> 00:47:01.490
heard you singing "Defying
Gravity" in "Wicked,"

00:47:01.490 --> 00:47:03.520
it inspired me to
start singing lessons.

00:47:03.520 --> 00:47:05.500
Because I have no theater
background or singing

00:47:05.500 --> 00:47:06.000
background.

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:07.120
I'm a total geek.

00:47:07.120 --> 00:47:09.320
But I started taking private
lessons a couple years.

00:47:09.320 --> 00:47:11.245
I even started a
chorus here at work.

00:47:11.245 --> 00:47:13.550
And some of the
members are here.

00:47:13.550 --> 00:47:15.880
And just I've always
wanted to sing,

00:47:15.880 --> 00:47:18.800
but I've never felt as
inspired as I did when I heard

00:47:18.800 --> 00:47:20.380
you sing "Defying Gravity."

00:47:20.380 --> 00:47:22.780
And I just wanted to be able
to sing along with that.

00:47:22.780 --> 00:47:25.120
And my singing
instructor has also

00:47:25.120 --> 00:47:26.700
started off trying
to teach me how

00:47:26.700 --> 00:47:28.970
to sing kind of like
you, the whole belt

00:47:28.970 --> 00:47:32.440
by shouting, which
is a lot like--

00:47:32.440 --> 00:47:33.750
IDINA MENZEL: Healthy shouting.

00:47:33.750 --> 00:47:36.149
AUDIENCE: Exactly, without
destroying my throat.

00:47:36.149 --> 00:47:38.690
IDINA MENZEL: Well, because like
children scream all the time

00:47:38.690 --> 00:47:41.070
and they never walk
around with laryngitis.

00:47:41.070 --> 00:47:43.610
So they do it in a
way that's very free.

00:47:43.610 --> 00:47:46.300
So that's the thought
process, not like screaming.

00:47:46.300 --> 00:47:49.375
It's that idea that you
call across the playground

00:47:49.375 --> 00:47:50.000
to your friend.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:51.860
You're like, hey, Johnny.

00:47:51.860 --> 00:47:53.370
And then you're like, hey!

00:47:53.370 --> 00:47:56.420
It's the same thing.

00:47:56.420 --> 00:47:57.520
That's how I think of it.

00:47:57.520 --> 00:48:00.620
And I would listen to Chaka
Kahn and Aretha Franklin

00:48:00.620 --> 00:48:02.990
and actually mimic
them all the time

00:48:02.990 --> 00:48:05.320
to figure out how
are they doing that.

00:48:05.320 --> 00:48:12.020
And so the best way to learn
I think is to emulate people.

00:48:12.020 --> 00:48:15.200
And then because we're who
we are, it'll never be them.

00:48:15.200 --> 00:48:17.420
It will still be
unique and true to us.

00:48:17.420 --> 00:48:20.759
So anyway, I cut you off.

00:48:20.759 --> 00:48:21.800
AUDIENCE: No, not at all.

00:48:21.800 --> 00:48:24.754
I just want to let you know how
your singing has touched me.

00:48:24.754 --> 00:48:25.920
IDINA MENZEL: Oh, thank you.

00:48:25.920 --> 00:48:26.770
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:48:26.770 --> 00:48:27.630
IDINA MENZEL: Thank you so much.

00:48:27.630 --> 00:48:29.330
So what are you
singing in the choir?

00:48:29.330 --> 00:48:30.940
What kind of music?

00:48:30.940 --> 00:48:34.120
AUDIENCE: We kind
of sing everything.

00:48:34.120 --> 00:48:35.830
We sing "Summertime."

00:48:35.830 --> 00:48:37.740
We sing Disney music.

00:48:37.740 --> 00:48:39.080
IDINA MENZEL: Oh, fun.

00:48:39.080 --> 00:48:43.700
That's great I actually
miss being in a choir.

00:48:43.700 --> 00:48:46.340
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
Well, maybe, if you

00:48:46.340 --> 00:48:52.830
would like to sing in a choir,
I'm just connecting dots here,

00:48:52.830 --> 00:48:53.870
as the moderator.

00:48:53.870 --> 00:48:56.186
It feels like
opportunities abound.

00:48:56.186 --> 00:48:57.810
IDINA MENZEL: I'm
very out of practice,

00:48:57.810 --> 00:49:01.380
though, with the four-part
harmony and everything.

00:49:01.380 --> 00:49:02.260
It's coed.

00:49:02.260 --> 00:49:03.959
It's obviously--

00:49:03.959 --> 00:49:05.417
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
It's very cool.

00:49:10.140 --> 00:49:12.390
AUDIENCE: So I have something
I've been wondering ever

00:49:12.390 --> 00:49:14.940
since I saw "Enchanted."

00:49:14.940 --> 00:49:18.260
And at this point,
you had very well

00:49:18.260 --> 00:49:21.420
established yourself, both
in terms of your acting

00:49:21.420 --> 00:49:23.320
and singing prowess.

00:49:23.320 --> 00:49:27.380
So it surprises me seeing
you in a musical movie role

00:49:27.380 --> 00:49:29.320
without a song in
the whole movie.

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:31.490
So do you have any thoughts on--

00:49:31.490 --> 00:49:34.230
IDINA MENZEL: Well, it wasn't
written as a singing part.

00:49:34.230 --> 00:49:35.950
And so I actually
was so flattered

00:49:35.950 --> 00:49:37.090
because I was like I know.

00:49:37.090 --> 00:49:37.720
I'm an actress.

00:49:37.720 --> 00:49:39.250
I'm not just a singer.

00:49:39.250 --> 00:49:40.840
So I was happy and
relieved to not

00:49:40.840 --> 00:49:42.006
have to worry about singing.

00:49:42.006 --> 00:49:45.310
Because a lot of
times it's a relief

00:49:45.310 --> 00:49:49.850
not to sing or to worry
about having it all there.

00:49:49.850 --> 00:49:51.420
So I was happy about that.

00:49:51.420 --> 00:49:53.500
But once I was in it,
they wrote something.

00:49:53.500 --> 00:49:56.370
And then it end up just being
superfluous because they

00:49:56.370 --> 00:49:57.590
were trying too hard.

00:49:57.590 --> 00:49:59.630
They wrote a whole song
for me and the prince

00:49:59.630 --> 00:50:02.830
at the end, James
Marsden, and it got cut.

00:50:02.830 --> 00:50:03.692
He knew it too.

00:50:03.692 --> 00:50:04.400
I was so excited.

00:50:04.400 --> 00:50:06.500
And he's like, this
is totally ending up

00:50:06.500 --> 00:50:08.310
on the cutting room floor.

00:50:08.310 --> 00:50:09.439
I was like, no, it's not.

00:50:09.439 --> 00:50:09.980
It's awesome.

00:50:09.980 --> 00:50:12.605
He's like, there's no reason for
this song to be in this movie.

00:50:12.605 --> 00:50:14.710
They're going to totally cut it.

00:50:14.710 --> 00:50:17.609
But thank you for
thinking of that.

00:50:17.609 --> 00:50:18.650
But I was actually happy.

00:50:18.650 --> 00:50:21.130
And then I got to take--
my first day of rehearsal

00:50:21.130 --> 00:50:23.480
in that movie, I had to
show up at a dance studio--

00:50:23.480 --> 00:50:26.780
a ballroom dance studio-- and
dance with Patrick Dempsey

00:50:26.780 --> 00:50:31.254
and James Marsden this close and
learned-- and I'm not a dancer.

00:50:31.254 --> 00:50:33.170
People think is I'm from
Broadway I can dance.

00:50:33.170 --> 00:50:34.830
I cannot.

00:50:34.830 --> 00:50:38.460
I have to have a special
session with the choreographer

00:50:38.460 --> 00:50:39.510
to teach me eight counts.

00:50:39.510 --> 00:50:42.480
That's like how bad
I am, but imagine

00:50:42.480 --> 00:50:45.470
having a go at those two hot
guys and like stand this close

00:50:45.470 --> 00:50:48.740
and try to be-- it
was heaven and it

00:50:48.740 --> 00:50:52.186
was hell at the same time.

00:50:52.186 --> 00:50:54.705
AUDIENCE: Well, thank you
for satisfying my curiosity.

00:50:54.705 --> 00:50:55.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:55.860 --> 00:50:57.610
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: I
think everybody just

00:50:57.610 --> 00:50:59.590
had this wonderful vision in
their heads of those two men

00:50:59.590 --> 00:51:00.810
at it exactly the same time.

00:51:00.810 --> 00:51:01.440
IDINA MENZEL: Oh, my god.

00:51:01.440 --> 00:51:03.780
And you have to have your butt--
it's like "Dirty Dancing."

00:51:03.780 --> 00:51:04.800
This is my dance space.

00:51:04.800 --> 00:51:07.990
This is your dance space.

00:51:07.990 --> 00:51:09.910
He's going to like
touch my arm, like that.

00:51:09.910 --> 00:51:13.605
You know how when Patrick
Swayze does that thing.

00:51:13.605 --> 00:51:14.980
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
It's so nice.

00:51:14.980 --> 00:51:17.012
IDINA MENZEL: And she's
like tickled by it.

00:51:17.012 --> 00:51:17.880
That's how I felt.

00:51:17.880 --> 00:51:18.820
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: Let's
all just take a moment

00:51:18.820 --> 00:51:19.922
and take that in for a second.

00:51:19.922 --> 00:51:21.210
IDINA MENZEL: You know what
I'm talking about, right?

00:51:21.210 --> 00:51:21.560
In the movie?

00:51:21.560 --> 00:51:22.059
OK.

00:51:22.059 --> 00:51:22.702
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:22.702 --> 00:51:23.910
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: Oh, yeah.

00:51:23.910 --> 00:51:27.490
Oh yeah, we got an
enthusiastic oh, yeah.

00:51:27.490 --> 00:51:28.930
Any other questions?

00:51:28.930 --> 00:51:30.681
We have time for one
or two more, anybody?

00:51:34.824 --> 00:51:35.740
AUDIENCE: Hi, I'm Tom.

00:51:35.740 --> 00:51:38.265
So I was wondering, do
you have a favorite song?

00:51:38.265 --> 00:51:42.020
And how often does your
favorite song change?

00:51:42.020 --> 00:51:44.230
IDINA MENZEL: Yeah, I don't
because it does change,

00:51:44.230 --> 00:51:47.209
depending on how I feel.

00:51:47.209 --> 00:51:49.000
I can tell you that
the things people would

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:52.030
think I get sick, like "Let
It Go" or "Defying Gravity,"

00:51:52.030 --> 00:51:55.370
I don't get sick
of singing them.

00:51:55.370 --> 00:51:58.070
Maybe it's the
creature of theater

00:51:58.070 --> 00:52:00.410
that I am, where you
are always looking

00:52:00.410 --> 00:52:03.300
for something new, just
the tiniest thing from show

00:52:03.300 --> 00:52:04.600
to show to keep it fresh.

00:52:04.600 --> 00:52:07.980
So that's an exercise
that I enjoy.

00:52:07.980 --> 00:52:11.692
So either it's a little
girl in the front row

00:52:11.692 --> 00:52:14.150
and I like, oh, I'm going to
sing "Let It Go" to her today.

00:52:14.150 --> 00:52:15.380
She never saw a concert.

00:52:15.380 --> 00:52:19.847
Or I think it to my son,
or I think of a new melody

00:52:19.847 --> 00:52:21.430
because I'm sick and
I have to come up

00:52:21.430 --> 00:52:23.240
with something different cause
I can't hit the high note.

00:52:23.240 --> 00:52:24.740
So then I'm like,
oh, that was cool.

00:52:24.740 --> 00:52:27.540
Whatever it is, I give
myself those exercises.

00:52:27.540 --> 00:52:29.860
So that can be fun.

00:52:29.860 --> 00:52:34.790
But it changes, depending
on the day, really.

00:52:34.790 --> 00:52:36.280
That's the cool
thing about music

00:52:36.280 --> 00:52:39.410
is like what you bring to it.

00:52:39.410 --> 00:52:44.280
The song kind of
unfolds differently.

00:52:44.280 --> 00:52:47.100
I used to sing "Both
Sides Now," Joni Mitchell,

00:52:47.100 --> 00:52:54.040
and that was a great song
that would sort of just reveal

00:52:54.040 --> 00:52:56.880
itself to me differently every
time I sang it, depending

00:52:56.880 --> 00:52:59.600
on what perspective I had.

00:52:59.600 --> 00:53:03.250
So that was nice.

00:53:03.250 --> 00:53:05.750
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: We hosted
you in the Joni Mitchell Room,

00:53:05.750 --> 00:53:06.670
without even knowing this.

00:53:06.670 --> 00:53:07.025
IDINA MENZEL: Oh, yeah?

00:53:07.025 --> 00:53:07.760
Is she here?

00:53:07.760 --> 00:53:08.620
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: That
is the conference room

00:53:08.620 --> 00:53:09.240
that we were in.

00:53:09.240 --> 00:53:09.370
IDINA MENZEL: Oh.

00:53:09.370 --> 00:53:10.660
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: It
was all Joni Mitchell.

00:53:10.660 --> 00:53:11.535
IDINA MENZEL: Really?

00:53:11.535 --> 00:53:14.694
JULIE ANN CROMMETT: Yeah,
look at that, everybody.

00:53:14.694 --> 00:53:16.360
I know we have to
wrap up because people

00:53:16.360 --> 00:53:18.509
have to get to
their next meetings,

00:53:18.509 --> 00:53:20.300
unfortunately, in the
workday, although I'm

00:53:20.300 --> 00:53:21.883
sure everybody would
like to stay here

00:53:21.883 --> 00:53:24.020
for another hour, yeah.

00:53:24.020 --> 00:53:28.960
If you could think of
one piece of advice

00:53:28.960 --> 00:53:31.910
that you received that you'd
want to share with all of us

00:53:31.910 --> 00:53:33.920
today, what's the thing
that always sticks out

00:53:33.920 --> 00:53:36.430
in your mind-- piece of advice?

00:53:36.930 --> 00:53:41.000
IDINA MENZEL: Is it
helpful in this arena?

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:43.460
I guess it could
be in life's arena.

00:53:48.240 --> 00:53:55.960
Yeah, it's just, I
feel like nobody's

00:53:55.960 --> 00:54:01.450
looking for a copy or a
clone of somebody else.

00:54:01.450 --> 00:54:05.690
So as much as we want
to be like other people

00:54:05.690 --> 00:54:07.720
and admire other
people, the more we

00:54:07.720 --> 00:54:11.150
figure out what makes
us completely unique,

00:54:11.150 --> 00:54:16.480
that will be the most desired
thing, whether it's in the arts

00:54:16.480 --> 00:54:19.410
or it's in business.

00:54:19.410 --> 00:54:21.690
So when you find that
thing that sets you apart,

00:54:21.690 --> 00:54:24.090
that's the thing that's
going to make you

00:54:24.090 --> 00:54:28.910
more desirable and successful.

00:54:28.910 --> 00:54:32.140
So like when we're
younger, we think

00:54:32.140 --> 00:54:36.270
we should be like other people.

00:54:36.270 --> 00:54:38.910
And it's not till we
realize that if we're

00:54:38.910 --> 00:54:43.830
as authentic as we can
possibly be, that eventually

00:54:43.830 --> 00:54:49.182
that you will reveal
yourself to the world.

00:54:49.182 --> 00:54:50.640
JULIE ANN CROMMETT:
That's awesome.

00:54:50.640 --> 00:54:51.520
Thank you for that.

00:54:51.520 --> 00:54:53.050
And thank you for being here.

